 Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>drake</i>, either ‘drake, male duck’ (compare   Duck  ) or ‘dragon’ (Old English <i>draca</i> ‘snake, dragon’ or the cognate Old Norse <i>draki</i>), including an emblematic dragon on a flag (compare   Dragon  ). Both the Old English and the Old Norse forms are from Latin <i>draco</i> ‘snake, monster’; its sense as a nickname is unclear but it may have had the sense ‘standard bearer’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century and reinforced by later English settlers in the 17th century.","German: from Low German <i>drake</i> ‘dragon’, familiar as image on signboards, hence a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn with such signboard.","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized and Flemish, of <b>Draak</b>, a cognate of 2 above, from <i>draak</i> (Middle Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Drakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."]}]},{"name":"Margareta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margareta Drake was born about 1390, in Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, her father, John Drake, was 42 and her mother, Christian Billett, was 38. She married Thomas Leighton in 1400, in Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1419, in Otterton, Devon, England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"about 1390–1419":"umbes 1390–1419","1388–1419":"1388–1419","1388–1449":"1388–1449","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1404–1479":"1404–1479","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1354–1430":"1354–1430","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1479":"1479","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","1419":"1419","1449":"1449","Otterton, Devonshire, England":"Otterton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1390–1419":"noin 1390–1419","1388–1419":"1388–1419","1388–1449":"1388–1449","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1404–1479":"1404–1479","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1354–1430":"1354–1430","about 1390":"noin 1390","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1479":"1479","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","1